# Decision Log – Breathe ESG Dashboard

## Project Overview

For this project, I decided to build a simple ESG Dashboard that can display and manage sustainability-related datasets in a clear and interactive way. The goal was to understand how ESG data can be handled using a full-stack web application.

The project mainly focuses on electricity usage, travel records, and fuel/material procurement data.

---

## Why I Chose React and Django

I selected React.js for the frontend because it makes it easier to create interactive user interfaces and dynamically display tables and buttons.

For the backend, I used Django REST Framework because it provides a simple way to create APIs and send data from CSV files to the frontend.

This combination also helped me understand how frontend and backend systems communicate in real-world applications.

---

## Data Handling Decisions

Instead of using a complex database, I chose CSV files for storing ESG data. This made the project easier to manage and allowed quick testing during development.

The CSV files were converted into JSON format through Django APIs so that the React frontend could display them properly.

Separate datasets were maintained for:
- Electricity
- Travel
- Fuel and Materials

---

## Dashboard Design Choices

I kept the user interface simple and readable instead of making it overly complex.

The dashboard includes:
- Search bar
- Upload button
- Review button
- Separate tabs for ESG categories
- Data tables for viewing records

The main focus was functionality and clarity rather than advanced styling.

---

## API Structure

Different API routes were created for each ESG category to keep the backend organized.

Examples:
- `/electricity/`
- `/travel/`
- `/fuel/`

This helped in testing and debugging each module independently.

---

## Deployment Decisions

For deployment:
- The frontend was deployed using Vercel
- The backend was deployed using Render
- GitHub was used for version control and project hosting

This setup allowed the project to run online and be accessible through a browser.

---

## Challenges Faced During Development

Several issues were faced during development, including:
- JSON parsing errors caused by invalid CSV values
- Deployment connection issues between frontend and backend
- Git commit and push issues
- Mobile responsiveness limitations

These problems were solved through debugging, updating API links, and fixing data formatting issues.

---

## Final Outcome

The final project successfully demonstrates:
- ESG data visualization
- Frontend and backend integration
- REST API usage
- Deployment workflow using modern platforms
- Basic ESG reporting dashboard functionality

This project also improved my understanding of full-stack development and deployment processes.